<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n38142b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n38" href="#n38142b">N38 (VI.B.32)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n38all.htm#n38142b"> 142(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> butter = / down in front / up at the back / down in back / backward jerk</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[decomposes &lsquo;butter&rsquo; in pantomimic mouth-gestures]</font> <i>Butter</i>: <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font>. The whole gesture therefore means: <mark>down in front (BA or BU), up at the back (-T), down at the back (TA) and a backward jerk (R)</mark>. <small> Sir Richard Paget, <a name="RPBP" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#RPBP"><cite title="source">Babel, or The Past, Present and Future of Human Speech</cite></a> (1930) 65</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: For Paget &ldquo;The gesture sequence suggests the action of moving the receptacle or plunger by which the cream was churned to butter &mdash; up and down forward and backward&rdquo;. Milesi adds: &ldquo;The principle will be applied to the word <i>heliotrope</i> in the girls&apos; mime of it in Chapter II.1, especially the first evocation on page 223, a fair-copy first draft (2.0) dated October-November 1930 in the <i>Archive</i> (BL-477-7; <cite>JJA</cite> 51:15 (cf. Selected Letters <a name="22Nov1930" href="../fbiog/fwlett.htm#22Nov1930">22 November</a> 1930).&rdquo;]  <br>Raphael transcription: <a name="c08005g" href="c08all.htm#c08005g">VI.C.08:005(g)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
